{{Infobox musical artist | honorific_prefix = | name = Lydia Lipkowska (Lypkivska in Ukrainian) | honorific_suffix = | image = Lydia Lipkowska 01.JPG | image_upright = | image_size = | landscape = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank --> | alt = | caption = Photograph published in ''The Grand Opera Singers of To-day'', 1922 | background = solo_singer | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | alias = | birth_date = 1882 | birth_place = Babyn, [[Kelmentsi]], [[Ukraine]] | origin = | death_date = 1958 | death_place = | education = Saint Petersburg Conservatory | genre = classical | occupation = | instrument = soprano | years_active = <!-- YYYY–YYYY (or –present) --> | label = | associated_acts = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} or {{Official URL}} --> | module = | module2 = | module3 = }}
'''Lydia''' [Yakolevna] '''Lipkowska''' (1882–1958) was a Russian [[opera]]tic [[soprano]] of [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] origin.
==Biography== [[File:LydiaLipkowska1921.tif|thumb|left|upright|<center>Lydia Lipkowska, from ''Music News,'' 1921</center>]] [[File:Photo_and_2_drawings_of_Lydia_Lipkowska_by_Marguerite_Martyn,_1910.jpg|thumb|right|<center>Lipkowska in drawings by [[Marguerite Martyn]], with a photo, 1910</center>]] Lydia was born in [[Babyn, Kelmentsi|Babyn]], where is a village museum dedicated to her, in the family of a rural teacher. Lydia had three sisters, four brothers. Her aunt was a famous Ukrainian actress Maria Zankovetska. She received education in the Mariinsky Women's Gymnasium in [[Kamyanets-Podilskyi]]. Together with other students, she sang in the church choir, she had her own solo parties, drawing attention with a magic voice that ran under the dome of the cathedral. Residents of Kamyanets called the girl "Singing Bird". After Kamyanets-Podiskyi Lipkowska was trained at the [[Saint Petersburg Conservatory]]. She was committed to the [[Mariinsky Theatre]] from 1906—1908 and again from 1911–1913. She was a member of the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in [[New York City]] from 1909<ref>{{cite journal | journal = New York Times | page = 9 | title = Metropolitan Plans Great Opera Season | date = 13 September 1909}}</ref> until 1911. Lipkowska's debut with the Metropolitan was as Violetta in ''[[La Traviata]]'' on November 18, 1909, with [[Enrico Caruso|Caruso]] as Alfredo.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = New York Times | date = 19 November 1909 | page = 11 | title = Traviata at Metropolitan: Mme. Lipkowska Makes Debut as Violetta &ndash; Caruso as Alfredo}}</ref> She sang as a guest artist at the [[Boston Opera Company]] in 1909 and the [[Chicago Grand Opera Company]] in 1910. While in Boston, Lipkowska was honored by [[The Lenox Hotel]], which put on its menu the "cup Lydia" and the "Souffle a la Lipkowska". She petioned a judge for an injunction against the hotel, claiming that the menu items were "injuring her reputation and holding her up to ridicule."<ref>{{cite journal | journal = New York Times | date = 16 February 1910 | page = 3 | title = Declines a Hotel's Homage}}</ref> In 1911 she made her debut at the [[Royal Opera House]] in London as Mimì in [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s ''[[La bohème]]''.
In 1912, Lipkowska charged New York gangster [[Sam Schepps]] with [[usury]] over his refusal to return two diamonds worth $80,000 that she'd pawned to him. Lipkowska said that she'd borrowed $12,000 from Schepps, had left the diamonds with him as security, and that he sought $5000 in interest before he would return the jewels.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = New York Times | date = 23 October 1921 | page = 18 | title = Lipkowska Accuses Broker of Usury}}</ref> In 1914 she sang in the world premiere of [[Amilcare Ponchielli]]'s ''[[I Mori di Valenza]]'' at the [[Opéra de Monte-Carlo]].
Lipkowska escaped from the [[Soviet Union]] with her then husband Pierre Bodin in 1920, arriving in New York on the [[RMS Adriatic (1907)|Adriatic]] of the [[White Star Line]] on February 8.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = New York Times | date = 9 February 1920 | page = 3 | title = Saved From 'Reds,' Singer Here a Bride}}</ref> In September 1920, Lipkowska sang Gilda in ''[[Rigoletto]]'' with the [[San Carlo Opera Company]] in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = New York Times | date = 22 September 1920 | page = 24 | title = 'Rigoletto' at Manhattan}}</ref> After retiring from the stage she lived in Romania where she was active as a voice teacher. One of her students was the soprano [[Virginia Zeani]]. She died in [[Beirut]] at the age of 75. For part of her life she was married to baritone [[Georges Baklanoff]].
